The paper deals with the k-means problem, which is a well-known problem in data science and machine learning. The problem involves finding k centers in a d-dimensional Euclidean space that minimize the sum of the squared distances of all points in an input set P to their closest respective center. This problem is closely related to clustering, which is a popular topic in computer science. Therefore, the most likely arXiv CS sub-category for this paper is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). 

The paper also discusses the inapproximability of the k-means objective, which is a topic that falls under the category of computational complexity. Therefore, the paper could also be classified under cs.CC (Computational Complexity). 

The paper uses mathematical techniques to establish the inapproximability of the k-means objective, which suggests that it could also be classified under cs.IT (Information Theory). 

The paper also discusses the results of previous research on the k-means problem, which suggests that it could be classified under cs.LG (Machine Learning). 

Finally, the paper deals with geometric concepts such as Euclidean space, which suggests that it could also be classified under cs.CG (Computational Geometry).
